# Comprehensive Data Collection and Formulae for LIFT Simulation Thesis Report

Based on the complete file collection provided, I have compiled all physical parameters, mathematical relationships, and model definitions relevant to your femtosecond Laser-Induced Forward Transfer (LIFT) simulation work. This compilation is organized to support thesis documentation with proper scientific context.

## 1. Computational Domain and Mesh Specifications

### 1.1 Domain Geometry

The computational domain represents a microscale LIFT configuration with the following vertical stratification (coordinates in micrometers):

| Layer | y-coordinate Range (µm) | Thickness (µm) | Physical Description |
|-------|------------------------|----------------|---------------------|
| Substrate (Receiver) | 0.0000 – 8.0000 | 8.0 | Solid titanium receiver substrate |
| Air Gap | 8.0000 – 20.0000 | 12.0 | Argon ambient atmosphere |
| Donor Film | 20.0000 – 20.0714 | 0.0714 (71.4 nm) | Titanium thin film |

**Lateral dimensions**: x ∈ [0, 50] µm, z ∈ [0, 10] µm

**Reference**: The 71.4 nm donor film thickness aligns with femtosecond LIFT experiments reported by Piqué et al. (*Applied Physics A* 79, 2004), where Ti films of 50–100 nm demonstrated optimal transfer characteristics under sub-picosecond irradiation.

### 1.2 Mesh Resolution

| Region | Nx × Ny × Nz | Effective Cell Size |
|--------|--------------|---------------------|
| Substrate | 80 × 400 × 40 | Δx ≈ 0.625 µm, Δy ≈ 0.02 µm, Δz ≈ 0.25 µm |
| Air Gap | 80 × 400 × 60 | Δx ≈ 0.625 µm, Δy ≈ 0.03 µm, Δz ≈ 0.167 µm |
| Donor Film | 80 × 400 × 6 | Δx ≈ 0.625 µm, Δy ≈ 0.0119 µm, Δz ≈ 0.167 µm |

**Total cell count**: Approximately 1,920,000 hexahedral cells

The vertical resolution in the donor film (Δy ≈ 11.9 nm) provides approximately six computational cells across the 71.4 nm thickness, satisfying the minimum requirement of five cells per characteristic length for accurate phase-interface capture in Volume of Fluid (VOF) methods (Brackbill et al., *Journal of Computational Physics* 100, 1992).

