## 2. Laser Source Parameters

### 2.1 Temporal Characteristics

| Parameter | Symbol | Value | Units | Source/Justification |
|-----------|--------|-------|-------|---------------------|
| Pulse energy | Ep | 60 | nJ | Threshold fluence ≈ 0.2 J/cm² for Ti LIFT (Piqué et al., 2004) |
| Pulse width (FWHM) | τp | 200 | fs | Typical fs-LIFT regime |
| Wavelength | λ | 343 | nm | UV absorption peak for titanium |
| Pulse repetition | fp | 0 | Hz | Single-pulse mode |
| Start time | tstart | 0 | s | Immediate activation |
| End time | tend | 200 | ps | Active phase duration |

### 2.2 Spatial Distribution

| Parameter | Symbol | Value | Units | Definition |
|-----------|--------|-------|-------|------------|
| Spot size (diameter) | D | 6.0 | µm | 1/e² beam diameter |
| Spot radius | w₀ | 3.0 | µm | Gaussian beam waist |
| Focus position | (xf, yf, zf) | (25, 20.0357, 5) | µm | Centered in donor film |
| Beam direction | **n** | (0, -1, 0) | — | Downward propagation (-y) |
| Spatial profile | — | Gaussian | — | I(r) = I₀ exp(-2r²/w₀²) |

**Reference**: The 3 µm beam radius provides a focal area of approximately 28.3 µm², yielding a peak fluence F₀ = Ep/(πw₀²/2) ≈ 0.21 J/cm² when accounting for Gaussian distribution, consistent with measured LIFT thresholds for titanium (Papazoglou & Zergioti, *Applied Surface Science* 197–198, 2002).

### 2.3 Absorption and Transmission

| Parameter | Symbol | Value | Units | Physical Basis |
|-----------|--------|-------|-------|----------------|
| Absorption coefficient (Ti) | α | 6.0×10⁷ | m⁻¹ | α = 4πk/λ, k ≈ 4.1 (Ti at 343 nm) |
| Penetration depth | δ = 1/α | 16.7 | nm | Effective absorption length |
| Reflectivity (air-Ti interface) | R | 0.35 | — | Fresnel calculation, normal incidence |
| Transmission coefficient | T = 1 - R | 0.65 | — | Energy entering metal |
| Gas absorption | αgas | 0 | m⁻¹ | Argon transparent at 343 nm |

**Penetration depth calculation**: With α = 6×10⁷ m⁻¹, approximately 63% of incident energy is absorbed within the first 17 nm of the 71.4 nm film, creating a steep thermal gradient that drives the two-temperature relaxation.

### 2.4 Intensity and Power Density

The peak volumetric power density q̇(r, t) delivered to the metal combines temporal and spatial Gaussian profiles:

$$q̇(r, t) = \frac{(1-R) \cdot I_0 \cdot \alpha \cdot \exp(-2r^2/w_0^2) \cdot \exp(-\alpha z)}{\sqrt{\pi/(2\ln 2)} \cdot \tau_p} \exp\left[-\frac{4\ln 2 \cdot (t - t_c)^2}{\tau_p^2}\right]$$

where:
- I₀ = 2Ep/(πw₀²τp√(π/(4ln2))) is the peak intensity
- tc is the pulse center time
- z is the depth into the metal (measured from y = 20.0000 µm)

**Calculated peak**: I₀ ≈ 3.5×10¹³ W/m², yielding maximum volumetric source q̇max ≈ 1.4×10²¹ W/m³ at the film surface during pulse peak. This value is capped at 10²⁴ W/m³ (parameter `maxVolumetricSource`) to prevent numerical instabilities while remaining physically reasonable for femtosecond ablation regimes.

