## 16. Model Hierarchy and Physics Coupling

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│          Laser Energy Input (fs pulse)              │
│              q̇_laser(r,t)                           │
└────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┘
                 │
                 ↓
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│    Electron Subsystem (Te)                          │
│    - Heat capacity: Ce(Te) = γTe                    │
│    - Diffusion: ke = Ce·De                          │
│    - Time scale: τe-ph ~ 1-25 ps                    │
└────────┬──────────────────────────────┬─────────────┘
         │ Coupling: G(Te)(Te-Tl)       │
         ↓                              ↓
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│    Lattice Subsystem (Tl)                           │
│    - Heat capacity: Cl = const                      │
│    - Phase transitions: Tsol, Tvap                  │
│    - Time scale: τl ~ 25-100 ps                     │
└────────┬────────────────┬────────────┬──────────────┘
         │                │            │
         │ (Tl > Tvap)    │ (Gas)      │ (Interface)
         ↓                ↓            ↓
    ┌─────────┐   ┌───────────┐  ┌──────────────┐
    │ Phase   │   │ Gas-Metal │  │ VOF          │
    │ Change  │   │ Coupling  │  │ Transport    │
    │ j, precoil│ │ hKapitza  │  │ ∂α/∂t+∇·(uα) │
    └────┬────┘   └─────┬─────┘  └──────┬───────┘
         │              │                │
         └──────────────┴────────────────┘
                        │
                        ↓
         ┌──────────────────────────────┐
         │   Momentum Equation (u)      │
         │   - Recoil force             │
         │   - Surface tension          │
         │   - Viscous dissipation      │
         └──────────────────────────────┘
```

---

This comprehensive data collection provides all fundamental parameters, equations, physical models, and numerical settings required to document your femtosecond LIFT simulation work. Each value is traceable to either experimental measurements, theoretical models, or established numerical practices, ensuring scientific rigor for thesis presentation.

**Note on file inconsistencies identified**: The `thermophysicalProperties.air` file specifies `rhoConst` (constant density) while the main `thermophysicalProperties` uses `perfectGas`. For compressible multiphase flow, the `perfectGas` model should be applied uniformly to ensure thermodynamic consistency between pressure, density, and temperature fields.
